Why Jerome Powell must go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as head of the US Federal Reserve – that is, to the possibly most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here can have serious consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to properly regulate the banking system, thereby setting the stage for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the reactions of political decision-makers to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting sense of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a number of clichés as to why the current Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell should be confirmed in office.
It would be a proof of bipartisanism.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
A used person with experience would lead us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I had already heard 25 years ago, when I was chairman of President Bill Clinton's economic advisory staff and the confirmation of Greenspan was the topic.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country has paid a heavy price for its decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan gave little attention to these arguments when, in 1987, he effectively fired Paul Volcker and denied Volcker a second term, even though Volcker had successfully tamed inflation.
Reagan owed much to Volcker, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, a follower of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful evaluation and sensitivity to conflicting objectives are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that the markets are efficient, stable, fair, and characterized by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the United States always represented clearly distinct, yet clearly articulated viewpoints on these issues (at least until the Republicans succumbed to the populist frenzy).
In my view, the Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis showed that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
In addition, we know that traditionally, only during tense labor markets have marginalized groups been integrated into the economy and wage differences have been reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a test for every US Federal Reserve chairman.
The United States is already facing difficult decisions on how to combat inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially problems stemming from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate of African Americans, which has not yet recovered to its pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and consequently an increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While the mispricing of mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of a stronger and more widespread mispricing of assets linked to climate change.
What should the Federal Reserve do in this regard?
Powell is not the man of the hour.
At first, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump, thereby risking the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding the climate risk, although other central bankers around the world have already declared it to be the central issue of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues are not within the Fed's mandate, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Federal Reserve's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such a laxity is the last thing the economy currently needs.
An obvious market failure and the lack of sufficient regulation already allow excessive profits, reduce credit availability to small businesses, and give dominant actors more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
But every student in their second year would have known that during a recession, one must not tighten monetary policy or raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argues, Powell does not feel particularly strongly committed to full employment.
On the contrary, Powell's record as a member of the Federal Reserve Board regarding the tightening of monetary policy over the past decade has been marked by a series of misjudgments that date back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed-watchers insist that inequality is not the Fed's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policies have significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early increase in interest rates can strangle growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentration of market power.
And finally, the latest scandal involving stock trading by top Fed officials has undermined confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparent lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including in the administration of some Federal programs in response to the pandemic, has been a concern of mine for a long time.
After four years of Trump weakening trust in US institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the central bank's integrity will suffer further.
No Fed representative should need an ethics officer who decides when certain stock transactions would appear inappropriate.
The Fed resembles the US Supreme Court to some extent.
This is supposed to stand above politics, but we have known since Bush v. Gore that this is not the case.
Trump has made it clear to everyone who still had doubts.
The Fed is also supposed to be independent, but Powell and Greenspan clearly demonstrated that this is not the case either, as they followed their party's deregulation agenda.
Yet while the central bank's board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power has traditionally been concentrated in the hands of the central bank chief — far more so than with the chief justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the central bank governor who decides which matters come to a vote and which topics are postponed or prioritized.
The climate issue is just one example where it is extremely important who sits at the head of the table.
The United States need a central bank that truly commits itself to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Anyone who believes that we can rely on uncontrolled markets or that regulation has already gone too far lacks insight.
We neither need an ideologue like Greenspan nor a Wall Street-friendly lawyer like Powell.
Someone is needed who has deep economic understanding and shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There is undoubtedly a lot of people who meet these conditions.
But Biden doesn't have to look far to find someone who has already demonstrated his abilities.
Lael Brainard is already sitting on the Federal Reserve Board, where she has demonstrated her expertise and won the trust of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank chair who maintains continuity and doesn't cause market turmoil, but who also shares his economic and social agenda.
